I like the puzzle. Took me about 5 minutes to get a solution, 7 minutes total to fix a bug due to row/col swaps I accidentally did, after about 1 minute planning. I like the complexity, as it's rather simple in it's approach.

Like Brunin said, There is probably some mapping that can be done to go faster or even golf it, and I look forward to seeing it discovered.

My solution in Kotlin:
import java.util.*
import java.math.*

fun main(args : Array<String>) {
    val input = Scanner(System.`in`)
    val symbols = input.nextLine()
    val width = input.nextInt()
    val height = input.nextInt()
    val grid = Array(height){ Array(width) { '.' } }
    for(row in 0 until height)
    {
        for(col in 0 until width)
        {
            grid[row][col] = symbols.toCharArray()[distToEdge(row,col,height,width)%(symbols.length)]
        }
    }

    grid.forEach{row -> 
    row.forEach{
        print(it)
    }
    println()}
}
fun distToEdge(x:Int,y:Int,a:Int,b:Int)=Math.max(listOf(x,y,a-x-1,b-y-1).min()!!,0)

This is an enjoyable puzzle. It seems harder than it really is at first. The easier solution is to find the minimum distance from any of the 4 sides. See my solution below.

const symbols = readline();
const len = symbols.length;

const [width, height] = readline().split(' ').map(Number);

for (let i = 0; i < height; ++i) {
    let row = '';

    for (let j = 0; j < width; ++j) {
        const depth = Math.min(i, height - i - 1, j, width - j - 1);
        row += symbols[depth % len];
    }

    print(row);
}
